               <interp inst="t18561027-1068" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18561027"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18561027-1068" type="date" value="18561027"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18561027-1068-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1068-18561027 t18561027-1068-offence-1 t18561027-1068-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1068. <persName id="def1-1068-18561027" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1068-18561027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1068-18561027" type="surname" value="SMALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1068-18561027" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOSEPH SMALL</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18561027-1068-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18561027-1068-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18561027-1068-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp>. feloniously uttering two 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. notes, with intent to defraud.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MESSRS GIFFARD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">BAILEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-741" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-741" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-741" type="surname" value="PALMER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-741" type="given" value="EMILY"></interp>EMILY PALMER</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my uncle, a dairyman, at Camberwell, the prisoner is a tenant of my uncle's. On Wednesday, 1st Oct., lie came and asked me if I would take 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for two weeks' rent, and give him the change for a 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note—I took the note, and I noticed two names on it—this is the note—here is the name of Thomas Taylor on it—I asked the prisoner to write his name, and he did so—I took 12<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., and gave him 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 8<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—I passed the note away in the course of business, and it was returned as forged—on Saturday, 4th Oct., the prisoner came again about half-past 9 o'clock—he had a note in his hand, and he asked me if I would give him change for it—I took it, and looked at it—I said, "It appears to be a good one"—he said, "I hope it is, I had it from my father in the country—I returned it to him, and said that I had not enough change—he asked me if I would send over to the Waterloo Arms to get it changed for him, as he was a stranger there, and the people did not like changing a note for him—I said, "I should think any of the houses you are in the habit of using would change it for you"—he then asked me if I would give him 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and give his wife the remainder on Monday morning—I told him I could not do it—I did not send him for change on that or any other day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METTCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You hare collected the prisoner's nut for some time for your uncle? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; the prisoner has been living there about two years—not a quarter of a mile from us—I knew him well, and he knew me—I did not see him very often—I received the rent from his wife generally—it is a private house where I live.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-742" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-742" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-742" type="surname" value="LEWTY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-742" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>JANE LEWTY</persName>
                  </hi>, jun. My father keeps the Waterloo Arms, at Gamberwell On Saturday afternoon, 4th Oct., the prisoner came—I was standing at the bar—he said, "Can you give me change for a 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note, for Miss Palmer; I wish to pay her some money, and she has only change sufficient to pay the men"—I took the note to my mother, in the bar parlour—she gave it me back, and told me to give change for it—I gave the prisoner four sovereigns and 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. worth of silver—I gave him a pen and ink, and told him to write his name on the note, and he did so—he asked if he should write his address—I said, "Yes, if you please"—he did so—this is the note—in the course of the next week it was returned as forged.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> In consequence of this address you went to him and found him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; my brother found the note was forged, and the pri<lb></lb>soner came to our house on the Sunday.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-743" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-743" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-743" type="surname" value="LEWTY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-743" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>JANE LEWTY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the mother of the last witness. I received a 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. note from her oh that Saturday—I took it upstairs—I brought it back, and gave it to her.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="185610270176"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-744" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-744" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-744" type="surname" value="LEWTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-744" type="given" value="BENNETT"></interp>BENNETT LEWTT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the son of the last witness. On Sunday, 12th Oct., in consequence of the note being returned, I went to the address on the note, to No. 11, Acorn-street, between 7 and 8 o'clock in the evening—the prisoner was in bed—I stood outside for a minute or two, and the pri<lb></lb>soner came out—I asked him to walk to our house with me—he had no jacket or boots on—he went back and put them on, and came out with them—he came to our bar parlour—the note laid on the table in such a position that he could see it—I told him that the note that my sister had changed for him had come back from the bankers, and they believed it was forged—he said, "Is it? I was not aware of it; I suppose I must get you the money"—I asked him where he got it from—he said, "I don't think I am bound to tell you"—I told him he had better, or it would be a very bad job for us both, and cause a great deal of trouble—he said, "I will tell you then; I found two of them in a brass-bound <hi rend="italic">ports monnaie</hi>, in the Borough, and I gave the other to my landlord"—I said, "Did you?"—I then said I would go to the Bank in the morning, and if it was a forgery I would come down to his house—he said, "Very well"—I went to his home the next day, about half-past 2 o'clock—I had then been to the Bank, and found the note was forged—when I got to the house the door was shut—I did not see the prisoner—I saw the lodger—I believe the prisoner has a wife; I did not see her—I went to the Peckham police station, and gave information to sergeant Bond—on Thursday, 16th Oct, I went with ser<lb></lb>geant Bond to No. 9, York-terrace, Peckham, and found the prisoner there with two children.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> In what part of Camberwell is Acorn-street? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> About a quarter of a mile from, the Green—the prisoner did not tell me that he picked them up on 19th Sept.—he said that he waited for some time to see if they would be advertised for, and that he took them to some tradesman, whose name he mentioned, to see if they were good—I cannot recollect that he told me that there was a shilling and a sixpence in the <hi rend="italic">porte monnaie</hi> besides the notes—when I went to his house, I did not tell him what I wanted him for, till he came to our bar parlour, and he walked in with me, and looked at the note—he did not say that he must go in the country to get the money—he said he would try and get it—he said after<lb></lb>wards that he had been to a friend of his in the country to try to get it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did he and his wife both tell you that they had been trying to raise the 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and if you had not given them into custody at that time, they should have raised the money? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have no recollection of his saying that—he told me that he had been to a friend, who had promised to advance it for him, and he should have raised it if I had not taken him—he said that he had been in the country to his father.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-745" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-745" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-745" type="surname" value="BOND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-745" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BOND</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">police sergeant, S</hi> 26). I went with the last witness to Acorn-street, on Monday, 13th Oct, I went there on several subsequent occa<lb></lb>sions—I did not find the prisoner on any occasion—on 16th, I went with Mr. Lewty to No. 9, York-terrace, and took the prisoner—I searched him at the station, but I found nothing on him—from Acorn-street to No. 9, York-terrace, is about a mile.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18561027-name-746" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-746" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-746" type="surname" value="BUMSTEAD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18561027-name-746" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH BUMSTEAD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am an inspector of notes to the Bank of England. These are forgeries, and both from the same plate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Are they very good imitations? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, they are such as might impose upon persons not acquainted with them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">to</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">EMILY PALMER</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you receive the rents of this man? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, for the house in Acorn-street—he had not given any notice to quit there.</p>
